<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">MM Strategy Tips</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">MM is a bingo machine:</span> SWIMMING, COMMAND, SHIMMER, STAMMER, DRUMMER, MAMMAL — MM words naturally reach 7+ letters. If you draw two M's, think bingo first before settling for a shorter play.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Use -MMING for verb extensions:</span> SWIM→SWIMMING, HUM→HUMMING, DRUM→DRUMMING. Any verb ending in M doubles it before -ING. Keep -ING tiles if you have M on your rack.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">-MMY endings pair with power tiles:</span> JAMMY(19), HAMMY(15), YUMMY(15), DUMMY(13) — the Y(4) suffix plus a high-value front consonant makes 5-letter -MMY words punch well above their length.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Place M on Double Letter Score:</span> M at 3 points becomes 6 on DLS. With two M's in the word, that is potentially 9 points from the MM pair alone on one premium square. Look for DLS alignment.</p>
  </div>
</div>

